  <div style="margin-top:2px;" class="detail-grid">
    <div class="detail-section ab3">
      <div class="slabel">⊛ Firmware Architecture</div>
      <p class="stext">The firmware is structured into three cooperating layers. The lowest layer provides a line_sensors_read() driver returning a calibrated position value (0–4000). The PID controller computes error = position − 2000, maintains a running integral clamped to I_TERM_MAX=150, and outputs differential speed corrections. The intersection FSM classifies junctions (L, R, S, B, T) using the inch-forward technique. The left-hand rule priority table selects the turn direction, pushed to the path array. After the end node is found, simplify_path() performs multi-pass reduction (L-U-L→S, etc.) to produce the optimal second-run route.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="detail-section abg">
      <div class="slabel">◈ Determinism &amp; Hard Real-Time Guarantees</div>
      <p class="stext">The PID loop runs on every main-loop iteration with no OS preemption. Turn routines use calibrated delay-based timing (g_turnDelay_ms = 200 ms) rather than sensor polling during turns — bounded execution. The path array is statically sized (128 entries) so no dynamic allocation occurs. OLED writes are batched after decision points and do not occur inside the PID loop. Interrupt-driven motor PWM runs independently at hardware timer frequency, guaranteeing consistent motor actuation regardless of firmware execution variance.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
